ows the fruitfulness of studying contemporary and modern texts alongside the traditional textual sources that informed them.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 0aJewish mourning customsxPhilosophy. 0aJewish philosophy. 0aLaments in the Bible. 0aLamentsxPhilosophy. 4aJüdisches Denken. 4aKlage. 4aScholem, Gershom. 4aTrauer. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Jewish Studies.2bisacsh  aGershom Scholem.  aJewish Thought.  aLament.  aMourning.1 aBarouch, Lina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBielik-Robson, Agata, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aComay, Rebecca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFerber, Ilit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFerber, Ilit, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHalbertal, Moshe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHamacher, Werner, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHasan-Rokem, Galit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLipszyc, Adam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMadar, Vered, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSauter, Caroline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aScholem, Gershom, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchonfeld, Eli, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchwebel, Paula, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchwebel, Paula, eeditor.4edt4